  </section> */}

  <!-- Tests Grid -->
  <section class="tests-section" id="tests">
    <div class="tests-inner">
      <div class="tests-header">
        <span class="mono-label">Display Tests</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Choose a test</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="tests-grid">
        {tests.map(test => (
          <TestCard
            title={test.title}
            description={test.description}
            href={test.href}
            icon={test.icon}
            
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Features section -->
  <section class="features-section">
    <div class="features-inner">
      <div class="feature-item">
        <div class="feature-icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
            <path d="M10 2L2 7v6l8 5 8-5V7L10 2z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            <path d="M10 12V7m0 0L7 9m3-2l3 2" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="feature-title">No data collected</h3>
          <p class="feature-body">All tests run entirely in your browser. No camera, no uploads, no telemetry.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-item">
        <div class="feature-icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
            <rect x="2" y="4" width="16" height="12" rx="2" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
            <path d="M6 10h8M10 6v8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Works on all devices</h3>
          <p class="feature-body">Phone, tablet, laptop, or desktop monitor — every test adapts to your screen.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-item">
        <div class="feature-icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
            <circle cx="10" cy="10" r="8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
            <path d="M7 10l2 2 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Zero installations</h3>
          <p class="feature-body">Open a URL, run a test. No app store, no extensions, no permissions needed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SEO Article Section -->
  <section class="seo-article-section" aria-label="About TestMyDisplay">
    <div class="seo-article-inner">
      <article class="seo-article">
        <h2 class="seo-article-title">Free Display Test — Check Any Screen Online</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>TestMyDisplay</strong> is a free <strong>display test online</strong> tool that runs
          entirely in your browser — no downloads, no sign-ups. A quick <strong>screen test</strong> takes
          under five minutes and can catch defects before a warranty window closes. Works on every device:
          phone, tablet, laptop, or external monitor.
        </p>

        <h3>What Each Test Checks</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dead Pixel Check</strong> — Cycles solid colors fullscreen to expose any pixel that never changes. Works on LCD, <strong>OLED</strong>, and <strong>AMOLED</strong> panels.</li>
          <li><strong>Touch Screen Test</strong> — Lights up a grid zone-by-zone as you slide your finger. Essential after a screen repair or for a <strong>mobile display test</strong> on a second-hand device.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-Touch Test</strong> — Counts how many simultaneous touch points your digitizer actually registers.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh Rate Test</strong> — Frame-timing analysis that measures your panel's real Hz — useful for any <strong>monitor display test</strong> or ProMotion <strong>iPhone display test</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>Backlight Bleed Test</strong> — Pure-black fill reveals IPS glow or light leaking from display edges.</li>
          <li><strong>Response Time Test</strong> — Moving-object animation to visually assess pixel response and ghosting on gaming monitors.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>OLED, AMOLED & All Panel Types</h3>
        <p>
          Each pixel on an <strong>OLED screen test</strong> or <strong>AMOLED display test</strong> is
          self-lit, so defects show differently than on LCD. The dead pixel checker and color fills are
          optimized for both. The refresh rate test also confirms adaptive ProMotion scaling on iPhones.
        </p>

        <h3>Fully Private — Runs Offline in Your Browser</h3>
        <p>
          Every <strong>screen display test</strong> uses standard Web APIs only. No camera access, no
          uploads, no telemetry. Safe on any network and works offline once the page loads.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="faq-inner">
      <div class="faq-header">
        <span class="faq-label">FAQ</span>
        <h2 class="faq-title" id="faq-heading">Common Display Test Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test my display's refresh rate?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Use the <a href="/tests/refresh-rate">Refresh Rate Test</a> on this site. It uses <code>requestAnimationFrame</code> timestamps to calculate the interval between frames and derives your display's actual Hz. Run it for at least 5 seconds for a stable reading — your result (e.g. 60, 120, 144, 240 Hz) appears in the large counter on the test page.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test an LCD display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>To fully test an LCD display, check four key areas: <strong>dead or stuck pixels</strong> (cycle solid red, green, blue, white, and black fills), <strong>backlight bleed</strong> (view a pure black screen in a dark room), <strong>refresh rate</strong> (verify the panel hits its rated Hz), and <strong>touch accuracy</strong> if it's a touchscreen. All four tests are available free on TestMyDisplay — no downloads needed.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test an OLED display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>OLED pixels self-emit light, so backlight bleed isn't a concern — but three checks matter most: <strong>dead pixels</strong> (a dead OLED pixel stays permanently black), <strong>burn-in / image retention</strong> (display a uniform mid-gray and look for ghost outlines of static UI elements), and <strong>refresh rate</strong> (most modern OLEDs run at 120 Hz or higher). Use the Dead Pixel and Refresh Rate tests here to cover all three.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test an iPhone display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Open any test on this site in Safari on your iPhone — all tests run directly in the browser with no app needed. The <a href="/tests/refresh-rate">Refresh Rate Test</a> correctly reads ProMotion (120 Hz) on supported models. For dead pixels, run the <a href="/tests/dead-pixel">Dead Pixel Check</a> in full-screen mode and swipe through each color. For touch issues, use the <a href="/tests/touch">Touch Screen Test</a> after a screen repair.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test a laptop display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Run this checklist on your laptop browser: (1) <strong>Refresh rate</strong> — compare this tool's reading with what your GPU driver reports under Display Settings. (2) <strong>Dead / stuck pixels</strong> — run the Dead Pixel Check at full brightness. (3) <strong>Backlight bleed</strong> — display a pure black page in a dark room and look for light leakage around edges. (4) <strong>Response time</strong> — check for ghosting during fast motion using the Response Time test. On Windows, <em>Settings → System → Display → Advanced display</em> also shows the advertised Hz.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I test a Retina display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Apple's Retina label means pixels are dense enough to be indistinguishable at a normal viewing distance. To verify it's working correctly: run the <a href="/tests/refresh-rate">Refresh Rate Test</a> (ProMotion Macs should hit 120 Hz), check for <strong>dead pixels</strong> on a solid white screen, and confirm gradients render smoothly without visible banding. On macOS, hold <kbd>Option</kbd> and open Display preferences to confirm the panel is running at its native HiDPI resolution.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What is a good refresh rate for a display?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 6l4 4 4-4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>60 Hz</strong> is the standard minimum for comfortable everyday use. <strong>90–120 Hz</strong> feels noticeably smoother for general browsing, video, and casual gaming. <strong>144 Hz and above</strong> benefits competitive gamers where reduced motion blur provides a real advantage. If the <a href="/tests/refresh-rate">Refresh Rate Test</a> reports a value significantly lower than your display's rated speed, check your GPU driver — you may need to manually select the higher refresh rate under Display Settings.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

